# CLAUDE.md.example

> A `CLAUDE.md` is like a toothbrush: useful daily, but don't use someone
> else's. This is a starting point, not a config to copy wholesale. Take it to
> your project (or `~/.claude/`) root, throw out what doesn't fit *your* mouth,
> and fill in the `<placeholders>` with your own habits.
>
> Sections marked **[core]** are near-universal — keep them. Sections marked
> **[pattern]** showcase a specific technique; adopt if it fits your workflow.
> `<!-- example: ... -->` blocks show the *shape* of a personal rule so you can
> write your own version — they are not defaults.

## Security 🔒 [core]

Never read/parse files holding secrets (keys, tokens, credentials, `.env`, certs).
Non-obvious ones too: `.npmrc`, `.pypirc`, cloud service-key JSON. If asked →
warn + require explicit confirmation.

## Communication [core]

- Clarify before big tasks; never hallucinate; say "I don't know" over speculation.

## Execution defaults [core]

Always-on biases for how work gets routed. Classify the task first, then go
straight to the right tier/tool — don't start big and walk back, or start blind
and escalate through failure.

- **Model** — don't default to your most expensive model. Route by task shape:
  chores → cheapest/fastest · single-file plumbing → mid-tier · strategy,
  hard refactors, security audits → top tier · very large context or multi-day
  work → your long-context model. Changing *effort* keeps the prompt cache
  (cheap); switching *model* breaks it (costly) — so switch models deliberately.
- **Sub-agents** — delegate to isolate context. Sweeping many files where only
  the conclusion matters → fan out to a cheaper model. Independent per-item work
  (2–6 items) → parallel sub-agents. Never shard cross-item reasoning or final
  synthesis — those stay on the main thread.

<!-- example: encode your own model-routing table here, e.g.
  chores → Haiku · plumbing → Sonnet · strategy/audit → Opus · >200K → <long-ctx model>
-->

## Planning [core]

- **Boulder → Pebbles**: boulders (multi-step, architectural, or ambiguous) get
  planned into trackable stories before work starts; pebbles (single file,
  obvious) just get done.

## Output style [core]

- **Human-facing output** (responses, docs, reports): visual-first. Prefer
  diagrams for flows/decisions/comparisons; structured data as clean YAML/JSON.
- **LLM-facing artifacts** (context files, specs, agent prompts): token-optimized.
  Strip prose, keep directives/facts/structure. No decoration.

<!-- example (Mermaid rules, if you use it):
  quote labels ["Label"] · multi-target A -->|label| B & C
  colored fills MUST include color:#000 for contrast
-->

## Temp files [core]

- Write throwaway files under a single dedicated scratch dir (e.g. `.tmp/{task}/`),
  never the system `/tmp`. Clean up when done.

## Git [pattern]

> This is a *boundary example*, not a default. Pick the posture that matches how
> you work and delete the rest.

<!-- example: hand git to the human
  User runs all git themselves — never invoke git, never add co-author/attribution
  tags. Write commit messages only when asked.
-->
<!-- example: let Claude commit
  Commit with Conventional Commits (type(scope): description). Branch off the
  default branch before committing. Never force-push shared branches.
-->
